#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:2
msgid "Quantum Annealing"
msgstr "Recuita quàntica"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:4
msgid ""
"In this tutorial, we will cover the basics of quantum annealing, and then"
" show how to use QiliSDK to implement a simple quantum annealing "
"algorithm."
msgstr ""
"En aquest tutorial, cobrirem els fonaments de la recuita quàntica i "
"després mostrarem com fer servir QiliSDK per implementar un algorisme "
"simple de recuita quàntica."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:8
msgid "What is Quantum Annealing?"
msgstr "Què és la recuita quàntica?"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:10
msgid ""
"Quantum annealing is a quantum optimization technique that is inspired by"
" the process of annealing in metallurgy, where a material is heated and "
"then slowly cooled to remove defects and improve its properties."
msgstr ""
"La recuita quàntica és una tècnica d'optimització quàntica inspirada en "
"el procés de recuita en metal·lúrgia, on un material s'escalfa i després "
"es refreda lentament per eliminar defectes i millorar les seves "
"propietats."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:14
msgid ""
"In quantum annealing, we start with a simple quantum system that is easy "
"to prepare and manipulate, and then we slowly evolve it into a more "
"complex system that encodes the solution to some problem we want to "
"solve."
msgstr ""
"En la recuita quàntica, comencem amb un sistema quàntic simple que és "
"fàcil de preparar i manipular, i després l'evolucionem lentament cap a un"
" sistema més complex que codifica la solució al problema que volem "
"resoldre."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:18
msgid ""
"There is a theorem (the adiabatic theorem) that states that if we evolve "
"our system slowly enough, we can guarantee that it will remain in its "
"ground state (the lowest energy state) throughout the evolution. The "
"speed that we need is determined by the energy gap between the ground "
"state and the first excited state, since if we have only a small gap "
"between the levels we have to move slowly to make sure we don't "
"accidentally jump up to the excited state."
msgstr ""
"Hi ha un teorema (el teorema adiabàtic) que estableix que si evolucionem "
"el nostre sistema prou lentament, podem garantir que romandrà en el seu "
"estat fonamental (l'estat d'energia més baixa) al llarg de l'evolució. La"
" velocitat que necessitem ve determinada per la bretxa d'energia entre "
"l'estat fonamental i el primer estat excitat, ja que si tenim una bretxa "
"petita entre els nivells hem de moure'ns lentament per assegurar-nos de "
"no saltar accidentalment a l'estat excitat."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:24
msgid "What is a Hamiltonian?"
msgstr "Què és un hamiltonià?"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:26
msgid ""
"When we talk about quantum annealing, we often talk about Hamiltonians. A"
" Hamiltonian is a mathematical object that describes the energy of a "
"quantum system."
msgstr ""
"Quan parlem de recuita quàntica, sovint parlem d'Hamiltonians. Un "
"Hamiltonià és un objecte matemàtic que descriu l'energia d'un sistema "
"quàntic."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:29
msgid ""
"In quantum annealing, we typically have two Hamiltonians: the initial "
"Hamiltonian, which is easy to prepare and manipulate, and the final "
"Hamiltonian, which encodes the solution to our problem. These are "
"combined into a single time-dependent Hamiltonian that evolves from the "
"initial to the final Hamiltonian over time:"
msgstr ""
"En la recuita quàntica, típicament tenim dos Hamiltonians: l'Hamiltonià "
"inicial, que és fàcil de preparar i manipular, i l'Hamiltonià final, que "
"codifica la solució al nostre problema. Aquests es combinen en un únic "
"Hamiltonià depenent del temps que evoluciona de l'Hamiltonià inicial al "
"final al llarg del temps:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:33
#, python-brace-format
msgid "H(t) = c_i(t) H_{initial} + c_f(t) H_{final}"
msgstr "H(t) = c_i(t) H_{initial} + c_f(t) H_{final}"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:37
msgid ""
"where :math:`c_i(t)` and :math:`c_f(t)` are time-dependent coefficients "
"that control how the two Hamiltonians mix over time."
msgstr ""
"on :math:`c_i(t)` i :math:`c_f(t)` són coeficients dependents del temps "
"que controlen com es barregen els dos Hamiltonians al llarg del temps."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:39
msgid ""
"These Hamiltonians are typically written in terms of the Pauli operators:"
" I, X, Y, and Z, which are a set of matrices operating on qubits that "
"form a basis for all possible quantum operations. So, for example, a "
"simple two-qubit Hamiltonian might look like:"
msgstr ""
"Aquests Hamiltonians s'escriuen típicament en termes dels operadors de "
"Pauli: I, X, Y i Z, que són un conjunt de matrius que operen sobre qubits"
" i formen una base per a totes les operacions quàntiques possibles. Per "
"exemple, un Hamiltonià simple de dos qubits podria tenir aquest aspecte:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:43
msgid "H = X \\otimes X - Z \\otimes I"
msgstr "H = X \\otimes X - Z \\otimes I"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:47
msgid ""
"where the first term represents an interaction between the two qubits, "
"and the second term represents a local field on the first qubit."
msgstr ""
"on el primer terme representa una interacció entre els dos qubits, i el "
"segon terme representa un camp local en el primer qubit."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:49
msgid ""
"For simplicity, the tensor product symbol (⊗) is often omitted, and we "
"can write the above Hamiltonian as:"
msgstr ""
"Per simplificar, el símbol del producte tensorial (⊗) s'omet sovint, i "
"podem escriure l'Hamiltonià anterior com:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:51
msgid "H = X(0)X(1) - Z(0)"
msgstr "H = X(0)X(1) - Z(0)"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:56
msgid "What Do We Do Once We Have a Hamiltonian?"
msgstr "Què fem un cop tenim un hamiltonià?"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:58
msgid ""
"Once we have a Hamiltonian that combines our initial and final "
"Hamiltonians, we can use it to evolve our quantum system over time. By "
"starting our system in the ground state of the initial Hamiltonian and "
"then slowly evolving it according to the time-dependent Hamiltonian, we "
"can hopefully end up in the ground state of the final Hamiltonian, which "
"encodes the solution to our problem."
msgstr ""
"Un cop tenim un Hamiltonià que combina els nostres Hamiltonians inicial i"
" final, podem fer-lo servir per evolucionar el nostre sistema quàntic al "
"llarg del temps. En iniciar el nostre sistema en l'estat fonamental de "
"l'Hamiltonià inicial i evolucionant-lo lentament d'acord amb l'Hamiltonià"
" depenent del temps, esperem acabar en l'estat fonamental de l'Hamiltonià"
" final, que codifica la solució al nostre problema."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:64
msgid ""
"Say our ground state is :math:`|ψ_0⟩`, we can represent the state of our "
"system at the next time :math:`dt` as:"
msgstr ""
"Si el nostre estat fonamental és :math:`|ψ_0⟩`, podem representar l'estat"
" del nostre sistema en l'instant següent :math:`dt` com:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:66
#, python-brace-format
msgid "|ψ(dt)⟩ = e^{-iH(dt)dt} |ψ_0⟩"
msgstr "|ψ(dt)⟩ = e^{-iH(dt)dt} |ψ_0⟩"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:70
msgid ""
"This process is repeated until we reach the end of our annealing "
"schedule. Assuming the :math:`dt` is small enough, the final state of our"
" system at the end of the process should be close to the ground state of "
"the final Hamiltonian, which encodes the solution to our problem."
msgstr ""
"Aquest procés es repeteix fins que arribem al final del nostre esquema de"
" recuita. Assumint que :math:`dt` és prou petit, l'estat final del nostre"
" sistema al final del procés hauria d'estar a prop de l'estat fonamental "
"de l'Hamiltonià final, que codifica la solució al nostre problema."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:76
msgid "How Do We Choose Our Hamiltonians?"
msgstr "Com triem els nostres hamiltonians?"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:78
msgid ""
"Determining what our initial and final Hamiltonians should be for a given"
" optimization problem is a non-trivial task, and there are many different"
" techniques for doing this. One common approach is to first represent our"
" optimization problem as a quadratic unconstrained binary optimization "
"(QUBO) problem, and then to convert this QUBO problem into our final "
"Hamiltonian."
msgstr ""
"Determinar quins haurien de ser els nostres Hamiltonians inicial i final "
"per a un problema d'optimització donat és una tasca no trivial, i hi ha "
"moltes tècniques diferents per fer-ho. Un enfocament comú és representar "
"primer el nostre problema d'optimització com un problema d'optimització "
"binària quadràtica sense restriccions (QUBO), i després convertir aquest "
"problema QUBO en el nostre Hamiltonià final."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:83
msgid ""
"A common starting Hamiltonian is the transverse field Hamiltonian, which "
"is given by:"
msgstr ""
"Un Hamiltonià inicial comú és l'Hamiltonià de camp transversal, que ve "
"donat per:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:85
#, python-brace-format
msgid "H_{initial} = - \\sum_i X(i)"
msgstr "H_{initial} = - \\sum_i X(i)"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:89
msgid ""
"This Hamiltonian has a simple ground state that is easy to prepare, which"
" makes it a good choice for the initial Hamiltonian in quantum annealing."
msgstr ""
"Aquest Hamiltonià té un estat fonamental simple que és fàcil de preparar,"
" la qual cosa el converteix en una bona elecció per a l'Hamiltonià "
"inicial en la recuita quàntica."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:92
msgid ""
"There is also the choice of how you want to schedule the annealing "
"process, which is determined by the functions :math:`c_i(t)` and "
":math:`c_f(t)`. Choosing a good schedule can be important for the success"
" of the annealing process, as it can help to ensure that we stay in the "
"ground state throughout the evolution. The simplest choice is a linear "
"schedule, the coefficients of which look as follows:"
msgstr ""
"També hi ha l'elecció de com es vol programar el procés de recuita, que "
"ve determinat per les funcions :math:`c_i(t)` i :math:`c_f(t)`. Triar un "
"bon esquema de programació pot ser important per a l'èxit del procés de "
"recuita, ja que pot ajudar a garantir que romanguem en l'estat fonamental"
" al llarg de l'evolució. L'elecció més simple és un esquema lineal, els "
"coeficients del qual tenen el següent aspecte:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:109
msgid "How Can We Simulate Annealing With QiliSDK?"
msgstr "Com podem simular la recuita amb QiliSDK?"

#: ../../shared/install_note.rst:1
msgid ""
"If you don't have QiliSDK installed and want to run the following "
"examples yourself, you can follow the instructions in the "
":doc:`installation guide </getting_started/installation>`."
msgstr ""
"Si no teniu QiliSDK instal·lat i voleu executar els exemples següents "
"vosaltres mateixos, podeu seguir les instruccions de la :doc:`guia "
"d'instal·lació </getting_started/installation>`."

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:113
msgid ""
"In order to test out our quantum annealing algorithm, we can use the "
"QiliSDK to simulate the annealing process on a classical computer. To do "
"this, we first create our initial and final Hamiltonians using the "
":doc:`Hamiltonian </modules/analog/analog_hamiltonian>` class, or more "
"specifically the Pauli operator classes:"
msgstr ""
"Per provar el nostre algorisme de recuita quàntica, podem fer servir "
"QiliSDK per simular el procés de recuita en un ordinador clàssic. Per "
"fer-ho, primer creem els nostres Hamiltonians inicial i final fent servir"
" la classe :doc:`Hamiltonian </modules/analog/analog_hamiltonian>`, o més"
" específicament les classes d'operadors de Pauli:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:124
msgid ""
"We then need to construct our schedule to determine how the mixing will "
"happen over time, which we can do using the :doc:`Schedule "
"</modules/analog/analog_schedule>` class. The class allows for complete "
"flexibility in how you want to define your schedule, but it also provides"
" some helper functions for common schedules:"
msgstr ""
"Després hem de construir el nostre esquema per determinar com es produirà "
"la barreja al llarg del temps, cosa que podem fer fent servir la classe "
":doc:`Schedule </modules/analog/analog_schedule>`. La classe permet una "
"flexibilitat total a l'hora de definir el vostre esquema, però també "
"proporciona algunes funcions d'ajuda per a esquemes habituals:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:134
msgid ""
"We want to start in the ground state of the initial Hamiltonian, which is"
" a uniform superposition of all possible states of the system:"
msgstr ""
"Volem començar en l'estat fonamental de l'Hamiltonià inicial, que és una "
"superposició uniforme de tots els estats possibles del sistema:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:142
msgid ""
"Finally, we can use :doc:`QiliSim </modules/backends/backends_qilisim>` "
"to simulate the annealing process:"
msgstr ""
"Finalment, podem fer servir :doc:`QiliSim "
"</modules/backends/backends_qilisim>` per simular el procés de recuita:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:157
msgid ""
"This gives us the expectation values of the observables we specified at "
"the end of the annealing process, which in this case are the terms in our"
" final Hamiltonian:"
msgstr ""
"Això ens dóna els valors esperats dels observables que vam especificar al"
" final del procés de recuita, que en aquest cas són els termes del nostre"
" Hamiltonià final:"

#: ../../tutorials/introductions/intro_annealing.rst:164
msgid ""
"These expectation values are close to the values we would expect for the "
"ground state of our final Hamiltonian, since to minimize the energy of "
"the final Hamiltonian we want to minimize the values of :math:`Z(0)` and "
":math:`Z(1)`, while maximizing the value of :math:`Z(0)Z(1)`. If we "
"increase the total time and decrease the time step, we can get these "
"values even closer to 1.0 and -1.0, at the cost of increasing the runtime"
" of our simulation."
msgstr ""
"Aquests valors esperats estan propers als que esperaríem per a l'estat "
"fonamental del nostre Hamiltonià final, ja que per minimitzar l'energia "
"de l'Hamiltonià final volem minimitzar els valors de :math:`Z(0)` i "
":math:`Z(1)`, mentre maximitzem el valor de :math:`Z(0)Z(1)`. Si "
"augmentem el temps total i reduïm el pas de temps, podem apropar encara "
"més aquests valors a 1.0 i -1.0, a costa d'augmentar el temps d'execució "
"de la nostra simulació."

